<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">
I'm not sure it'll give you much protection, the way I understand the change in the zoning mechanism means that no NPC's will aggro you <B>only if</B> the faction tables haven't loaded in.<P>This particular niggle only affects a very smal percentage of players, whereas the client (EQ softare at the players end) responding slowly is just a performance problem thats hard to work around.<P>Alot of people have asked for Verrant to insert some code to check if all graphics/sound have loaded after a zoning before activating the users client and making your character killable, however the problem with this is Windows memory management system can mislead programs into thinking data is in RAM, when it actually in the swapfile - and even when the data is physically in RAM, there is still going to be a slight delay while all the textures get copied across to the graphics card before you can see anything.<P>It all comes down to your PC's performance and how well it's setup, some people are always goign to have this problem although this is not one I've ever experiences here - even on a 56.6k dialup connection.  The biggest difference I noticed in EQ performance wasn't when going from a PII/400 to a PIII/800 or an old TNT/2 to GeForce2GTS card, but when going from 96mb to 256mb (upgrades done at different times), this really seemed to boost zoning speed, especially when you flick back and forth between zones.<P>The only sure way to fix it is build in an additional X amount of seconds after zonings where you are invincible, but I suspect Verrant would consider this measure has too much exploitation potential for it ever to happen.<P>Shanya, lvl 49, Innoruuk Server
</FONT>
